  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and detect money laundering. Key requirements include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Implementing internal compliance procedures\n- Training employees\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Identifying customer sources of funds\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n- Maintaining detailed customer information\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Following regulations like Bank Secrecy Act\n- Adhering to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Cooperating with international law enforcement\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant financial fines, criminal charges, and potential loss of operating licenses. These obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the global financial system's integrity.",
